    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Hey, I'm stuck on a section of my dissertation. I have a result where the p-value came out to 0.06. My advisor is being really strict about it not being \"statistically significant\" because it's above the 0.05 threshold, but it looks like there is a definite trend in the data. Can you explain the mathematical reasoning behind why we can't just call this significant, even if the trend looks real?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A p-value of 0.06, being above the conventional 0.05 threshold, means your data is not quite strong enough to *definitively* reject the null hypothesis. It means the evidence you have is a bit too weak, just a little bit of fuzziness, to declare a clear winner. Think of it like trying to catch a slippery eel with a net. You see the eel moving, you see the *trend*, but the net isn't quite tight enough to guarantee you've caught it.\n\nThe mathematical reasoning boils down to probability, which is where the true nature of the small-scale, slightly-off-center results lies. When you set your significance level ($\\alpha$) at 0.05, you are essentially saying, \"I am willing to accept a 5% chance that I'm seeing this trend purely by random chance, even if there's no real effect.\" Since your p-value is 0.06, that means there is a 6% chance that you are seeing this trend just because the data is noisy, or because the null hypothesis is true.\n\nIf you were to stick with $\\alpha = 0.05$,",
      "source": "target",
